al to the steadfastly unorthodox. Some were such avid students of theology that they were treated as equals by the leading ministers of their day. Others vacillated in their conviction. James Madison's religious beliefs appeared to weaken as he grew older. Thomas Jefferson, on the other hand, seemed to warm to religion late in life. This compilation lays out the founders' positions on more than seventy topics, including the afterlife, the death of loved ones, divorce, the raising of children, the reliability of biblical texts, and the nature of Islam and Judaism. Partisans of various stripes have long invoked "ations from the founding fathers to lend credence to their own views on religion and politics. This book, by contrast, is the first of its genre to be grounded in the careful examination of original documents by a professional historian. Conveniently arranged alphabetically by topic, it provides multiple viewpoints and accurate "ations. Readers of all religious persuasions--or of none--will find this book engrossing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aReligion. 7aREFERENCE / Quotations.2bisacsh  aAbigail Adams.  aAbsurdity.  aAdultery.  aAmerican Bible Society.  aApprobation.  aAtheism.  aAtrophy.  aBalthasar Bekker.  aBaptists.  aBenjamin Rush.  aBible.  aBook of Revelation.  aCalvin (Calvin and Hobbes).  aCalvinism.  aCapital punishment.  aCatechism.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholicism.  aChaplain.  aCharles Carroll of Carrollton.  aChristendom.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aClergy.  aCommon English Bible.  aCotton Mather.  aCreed.  aDeism.  aDeity.  aDespotism.  aDignity.  aDivine right of kings.  aDoctrine.  aDuty.  aEdition (book).  aEucharist.  aFable.  aFasting.  aForeknowledge.  aFreedom of religion.  aGentleness.  aGeorge Wh